o prior target ref, but other branches' commits serve as haves\n- **\"Other\" creates**: Same logic—uses existing target refs as haves\n\n**2. The Hidden Assumption** (`/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync/internal/planner/planner.go:321-326`):\n\n```go\n// Tags and other-kind refs don't generally form fast-forward chains\n// — a notes append creates a new commit that isn't an ancestor of the previous notes tip\n```\n\nThis comment hints at the real problem: **incremental assumes that wants are reachable from one of the haves**. With branches FF updates, this is guaranteed. With notes/pull refs, it's not.\n\n**3. The Pack Pruning Hole** (`/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync/internal/planner/planner.go:452-460`):\n\nIncremental's FetchPack prunes server-side: \"objects reachable from a have are absent from the local store.\" This works fine for branches/tags because:\n- You're updating to an ancestor of the old commit, OR\n- Creating new refs whose histories branch from existing ones\n\nBut for notes refs: you're creating a **new, disconnected commit history** that shares no ancestry with existing target refs. The source server's pack negotiation assumes all unreachable objects are in that pack. If incremental relay tries this with notes:\n\n1. Relay sends: want=notes_commit, haves=[all_current_target_refs]\n2. Source: \"notes_commit is unreachable from your haves, I'll include it\"\n3. **But the thin pack may be incomplete**: if notes_commit references objects that exist on target via some indirect path (blobs, etc.), they're pruned server-side and assumed reachable\n4. The thin pack lacks those objects\n5. Target receive-pack can't apply the update—missing referenced objects\n\n**4. Why Materialized Works** (`/Users/soph/Work/entire/devenv/git-sync/internal/strategy/materialized/materialized.go:93-105`):\n\nMaterialized:\n- Uses `FetchToStore` with the same haves negotiation\n- But then runs `ObjectsToPush` locally: walks the full closure from all wants, exc